
## Why Business‑Continuity (BC) Matters to a Small‑to‑Mid‑Size Company  

| What‑If Scenario | Typical Financial Impact | What BC does | Bottom‑line Value |
|-------------------|------------------------|------------|-------------------|
| **Server outage lasting 8 h** (average for a midsize firm) | $150 k × 8 h = $1.2 M lost revenue + $250 k‑$500 k remediation | Rapid fail‑over, pre‑defined recovery steps, automated alerts | **Revenue protected** – a 30 % downtime reduction saves $360 k per incident (Fixinc 2024) |
| **Regulatory audit discovers missing evidence** | Fines & remediation $200 k‑$1 M, reputational loss | Centralised, version‑controlled BCP, audit‑ready reports | **Compliance cost avoidance** – 15‑20 % penalty reduction = $30 k‑$200 k saved (MNP 2025) |
| **Supply‑chain disruption (single supplier fails)** | Production halt 3 days → $150 k × 72 h = $10.8 M (for a $200 M revenue firm) | Business‑impact analysis (BIA) flags critical suppliers, triggers alternate sourcing | **Operational continuity** – pre‑identified alternatives cut loss by > 70 % (Everbridge case study) |
| **Brand‑reputation hit after data‑breach** | Customer churn 5 % → $10 M revenue loss | Crisis‑communication hub, multi‑channel alerts, rapid containment | **Customer‑trust preservation** – faster notification reduces churn and saves millions (Deloitte 2024) |

> **Bottom line:** Every dollar spent on BC is a hedge against losses that are typically **10‑30 × larger** than the cost of the BC program itself.

